  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "David's mourning, and Joab's reproof. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 19:1-6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". When Joab was told that the king was mourning and weeping for Absalom, he went to him into the house to expostulate with him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 19:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " introduces the continuation of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 19:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 19:2-4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " contain parenthetical sentences, describing the impression made upon the people by the king's mourning. Through the king's deep trouble, the salvation (the victory) upon that day became mourning for all the people who had fought for David, and they went by stealth in to the city (לבוא יתגּנּב: they stole to come, came by stealth), \"as people steal away who have covered themselves with shame, when they flee in battle.\" ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
